    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3c324b60e71fd836",
      "text": "VI. Differenzierung / [[Differentiation]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1d519ac98e6f8e7f",
      "text": "The classical theory of power assumed separate, contradictory structures of [[Need]], i.e. social differentiation. It regarded differentiation as a found, naturally existing source of [[Conflict]] and thus as a cause for the development of power. This view could be considered adequate as long as the principle of segmenting differentiation prevailed in the world, i.e. a form of differentiation that placed approximately equal units next to each other: Families, tribes, states, societies. In the course of the development of civilization, however, these are increasingly being replaced by another, more efficient form of differentiation according to specific functions, which enables the creation of much more complex systems.129 [[Functional Differentiation]] forces the formation of ever more comprehensive social systems. These form subsystems according to specific functions, which in turn can neither be equal nor self-sufficient in relation to each other. "
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "0c5855935b6711e6",
      "text": "102–103"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f639dad04c3b263f",
      "text": "Such [[Functionally Specific Subsystems]] as churches, state bureaucracies, small families, commercial enterprises, nursing organizations, schools, armies, etc. become strongly interdependent on each other, which is anchored in the structure of the overall system, society, as a permanent formation of the status quo. Of course, segmenting differentiation still occurs, but it must now justify itself functionally.130"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6ccb0f2011bfe21c",
      "text": "Classical power theory is inadequate for describing power relations in such functionally differentiated social orders. A clear causal attribution of power possession and power effect is no longer possible due to the complexity of the relationships. Orientation towards the extreme case of ruthless struggle is also becoming increasingly unrealistic. To see this, one need only ask oneself what power the technicians responsible for air traffic safety have; or the surgeons; or the chairman of the budget committee of a parliament; or the large oil companies. "
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "e9d52239c678b672",
      "text": "103–104"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9f6b388f322ec856",
      "text": "Causal attribution is not possible in such cases, because all these subsystems can only exercise their power by submitting to the power of others and accepting already reduced complexity. Nor are extreme permanent conflicts conceivable without the overall system seeing this as a problem and looking for and finding functionally equivalent alternatives, i.e. procuring a (more or less costly, more or less adequate) replacement for blocked individual contributions and rebellious subsystems from the point of view of their specific function."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bcc83ef62f1f4f38",
      "text": "In fact, in functionally differentiated societies, the functional interdependence of the subsystems and the permanent considerations anchored therein largely replace elementary means of power such as loyalty or coercion as the basis of power. Conversely, large-scale functional differentiation can only develop if these elementary bases of power can be restructured and incorporated into the new order with specific functions. Because this is the case, the motivationally powerful loyalties must be differentiated with increasing functional differentiation, and the general order of values must take on more abstract, less directly binding forms (for example, be related to the \"nation\"). For the same reason, functional differentiation can only be achieved if the disposal of legitimate physical coercion is centralized and itself transformed into a specific function, which is carried out by the political-administrative subsystem of society according to certain rules."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "018cc0dd9241073d",
      "text": "104–105"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "020aec834bc9eacb",
      "text": "In this way, it is ensured that physical violence is accessible to all members of society in accordance with those rules, but that the centralization of decisions on the use of violence does not result in a corresponding concentration of power, but that power in such a society must now be largely based on functional dependencies. Only in this way can the need for power in highly differentiated societies be satisfied, and only in this way can it be prevented that the available power is reduced to the relatively low communication potential of those who program or decide on the use of physical force."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "13f5f7ca7a3af57e",
      "text": "Interrelationships of this kind, which have shaped the face of modern societies and their \"nation states\", could only be grasped in a very distorted and cumbersome way if one continued to assume that power is based solely on the ability to assert oneself in the event of conflict. Accordingly, the other premises of classical power theory must also be revised. Power in a functionally differentiated system is not transitive, but interspersed with reciprocal and circular structures, and it does not remain constant in terms of sum."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "ce1720deb7393512",
      "text": "105–106"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8e73421e5a56b9b6",
      "text": "If the complexity of the system, i.e. the number of options available to choose from, and the interdependencies in the system increase, the power of the system also increases. All subsystems can then, assuming appropriate organization, muster more power to limit the selection range of others, and will often have to accept more power influence in order to do so meaningfully (unless other mechanisms of transferring selection services, such as truth or love or money, step in). Discussions of \"democratic centralism\" in the East and group leadership in the West have independently suggested and, in rare moments of enlightenment, even articulated this insight. 132"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8fa168707846b5d9",
      "text": "For the classical causalist and action-theoretical approach to power theory, it can be said that it cannot do full justice to the phenomenon of functional-structural differentiation and its significance for the power situation in social systems. The reverse is true for the system-theoretical conception of power: that it must develop a theory of system differentiation because it cannot carry out its analyses in any other way."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6cb6922ae12d1901",
      "text": "Systems theory assumes, as shown, that all power is generated by processes of generalization in systems in order to satisfy the need for a transmission of completed selection services. Generalization is bound to systems because it requires the determination and constancy of boundaries."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "45c4788ed7c6e19e",
      "text": "106–107"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2193410788cc99f1",
      "text": "According to this, power only exists in the system. However, since there are obviously many systems, any analysis of power must be conducted in a system-relative manner and must first choose its reference system.133 An analysis of the international political system would emphasize completely different structures and processes and determine completely different intensities and distributions than the analysis of an Eskimo tribe, a broadcasting corporation or the political system of a nation state. For this reason, the system reference must be kept constant during an investigation, even if the power relations of different systems are connected. For example, it makes a difference whether one examines the power relations in the leading body of a party or the power of this body in the party, the power of this party in the political system of its society, the power of this political system in its politically united society or the power of this society in the international political system."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "205fa7650b56f143",
      "text": "By specifying the system under investigation, however, our problem is only solved in a very superficial meaning."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "628539942fa9be24",
      "text": "107–108"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1c445c3db0461900",
      "text": "In the analysis itself, it reappears in two forms:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aed7de8a4d1a4f9c",
      "text": "On the one hand, every system must be regarded as differentiated into subsystems.134 Although the question of how selection services are transferred between these primary subsystems is at the forefront of analytical interest, the answer to this question can never be completely separated from the question of how selection services are transferred within the subsystems, whether they have a lot of power (or truth, or money, or love) at their disposal and to what degree of temporal-objective-social generalization. In a political party, for example, there may be powerful cliques that can take a position quickly and unanimously on almost all issues due to their internal power relations and base their (for them external) internal party power on the fact that a united appearance and the ability to form consensus are rewarded in the party as facilitating decision-making. The power relations of the system under study can thus be co-determined by the internal organization of its subsystems due to its specific nature and problem constellation. However, this does not result from a simple summation and aggregation of the power of subsystems, which can also turn against each other."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "1e74dcf369e8c46c",
      "text": "108–109"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "410431ac10dc6151",
      "text": "Rather, subsystems and the overall system are inhomogeneous units between which power cannot be easily transferred. For this reason, the formation of power in subsystems is as indispensable as it is dangerous, and maintaining the reflexivity of power in the overall system - i.e. the applicability of its power to the power of the subsystems and of their power to its power - remains a permanent problem."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a581f7a26e8b903f",
      "text": "On the other hand, the same problem must also be considered at the outer boundaries of the respective reference system. System power, even if it is as completely generalized in temporal-objective-social terms as is conceivable, is not without further ado environmentally effective. A religious sect that has all the possibilities of internal decision-making and decision-making at its disposal may fall victim to ridicule, a political party may find itself in permanent opposition in its political system despite its high internal power. No one will deny the internal power of the Catholic Church in Poland, and yet politically it can be limited to a largely inconsequential presentation of views. Perhaps such borderline cases of functional differentiation are typically unstable because the system, thanks to its decisiveness, can either improve relations with the environment through restructuring or cannot maintain its high internal power in the long term. The applicability of system power in the environment, its effective, useful usability, \"is of course an unthinkable factor in the generalization of internal power."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "bde2c1c58ff147ef",
      "text": "109–110"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "86111150019ff39c",
      "text": "On the other hand, internal power is by no means eo ipso power that can be used as the power of the system in environmental relationships, since the opportunities for power that arise there are governed by the conditions of another system. The transmission of power across system boundaries is therefore also a problem here."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "94778a57f41d3468",
      "text": "If one looks at the structure of highly differentiated large-scale systems as a whole - for example from the point of view of a relatively large-scale, highly complex society - then the problem of these internal boundaries and the relatively low \"convertibility\" of internal power does indeed prove to be a critical obstacle to the consolidation of great power in one place. It may be that even at this system level there are still mechanisms of generalization of influence that can help to overcome this. These are questions that can only be asked speculatively and must be answered empirically. On the other hand, for precisely these reasons, large societies will do well if they do not rely primarily on power, but first and foremost on internally more easily convertible mechanisms for the transfer of selection services, namely truth and money. There is another obstacle to the concentration of power and it works in the same direction: the insufficient decision-making capacity of individual bodies."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "50d66b04073c900a",
      "text": "As long as the social structure was relatively simple and based primarily on kinship systems, i.e. segmenting differentiation, the power that could be mobilized was low:"
    },
