    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2a81e1514f56002e",
      "text": "There were few options to choose between. For the same reason, the political power of a ruler could essentially be about what kind of passion for collecting was satisfied, whether and how much treasure, troops, women, castles, sovereign rights or territories the ruler accumulated. The old problem of despotism rested on the assumption that systemic power and personal goals could be reconciled. In borderline cases, this kind of personal politics is of course still conceivable today, as a policy of territorial expansion, the collection of atomic bombs or prestige successes - but usually with serious dysfunctional consequences. Power increases so much through far-reaching differentiation that it can no longer be exhausted through capricious, arbitrary use of power.135 The \"autocrat\" lacks sufficiently differentiated motives. Basically, only very little power can be spent arbitrarily.136 "
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "4a710ee5c7f2be33",
      "text": "111–112"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "48213bc3c822955e",
      "text": "If system power becomes more generalized and more alternatives have to be eliminated with every decision due to increased complexity, it becomes obvious nonsense to allow a few motives to dominate. System power as a whole then eludes use by individual decision-makers. Every decision presupposes prior and subsequent contributory influences on the decision-making process. Accordingly, in a differentiated system, the organizational and communication services must be strengthened. Power is then so strongly generalized that it can only be exercised by assuming influence. Wherever it appears in the system, it exerts influence. This opportunity for influence can be exercised by other subsystems. In this respect, too, generalization of power and differentiation of structure are interdependent."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b774576ce6b8e549",
      "text": "Taken together, such considerations lead to the conclusion that the nature and strength of system differentiation should be taken into account as a central variable in power theory."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "3e5ffdea5c02f1cb",
      "text": "112–113"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ef61653fe9af0710",
      "text": "The complexity of the system, namely the number of options available and the interdependencies in the system, depend on it. Differentiation makes it possible to orientate oneself towards system boundaries and to distinguish between power in the system and power of the system. It determines the need for the transfer of completed selection services, the extent to which system power must be created to satisfy this need and the extent to which this power is convertible beyond system boundaries, so that internal selection is also recognized outside the system. None of this asserts a direct and fixed correlation between system differentiation and system power. In such considerations, for example, the factor of organization must not be neglected, the numerous mechanisms that enable influence processes to become reflexive must not be overlooked and, finally, the importance of calculation and the behavioural skills of those involved must not be underestimated. Nevertheless, the type and extent of system differentiation remain the variables that indicate the problems that must be solved for all system functions and thus also for the power mechanism if a system of corresponding complexity is to be created and maintained."
