    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "bcc83ef62f1f4f38",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "bcc83ef62f1f4f38",
        "text": "In fact, in functionally differentiated societies, the functional interdependence of the subsystems and the permanent considerations anchored therein largely replace elementary means of power such as loyalty or coercion as the basis of power. Conversely, large-scale functional differentiation can only develop if these elementary bases of power can be restructured and incorporated into the new order with specific functions. Because this is the case, the motivationally powerful loyalties must be differentiated with increasing functional differentiation, and the general order of values must take on more abstract, less directly binding forms (for example, be related to the \"nation\"). For the same reason, functional differentiation can only be achieved if the disposal of legitimate physical coercion is centralized and itself transformed into a specific function, which is carried out by the political-administrative subsystem of society according to certain rules."
      },
      "date": 1707399707930
