        "text": "According to this, power only exists in the system. However, since there are obviously many systems, any analysis of power must be conducted in a system-relative manner and must first choose its reference system.133 An analysis of the international political system would emphasize completely different structures and processes and determine completely different intensities and distributions than the analysis of an Eskimo tribe, a broadcasting corporation or the political system of a nation state. For this reason, the system reference must be kept constant during an investigation, even if the power relations of different systems are connected. For example, it makes a difference whether one examines the power relations in the leading body of a party or the power of this body in the party, the power of this party in the political system of its society, the power of this political system in its politically united society or the power of this society in the international political system."
