        "id": "aed7de8a4d1a4f9c",
        "text": "On the one hand, every system must be regarded as differentiated into subsystems.134 Although the question of how selection services are transferred between these primary subsystems is at the forefront of analytical interest, the answer to this question can never be completely separated from the question of how selection services are transferred within the subsystems, whether they have a lot of power (or truth, or money, or love) at their disposal and to what degree of temporal-objective-social generalization. In a political party, for example, there may be powerful cliques that can take a position quickly and unanimously on almost all issues due to their internal power relations and base their (for them external) internal party power on the fact that a united appearance and the ability to form consensus are rewarded in the party as facilitating decision-making. The power relations of the system under study can thus be co-determined by the internal organization of its subsystems due to its specific nature and problem constellation. However, this does not result from a simple summation and aggregation of the power of subsystems, which also turn against each other"
