      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a581f7a26e8b903f",
        "text": "On the other hand, the same problem must also be considered at the outer boundaries of the respective reference system. System power, even if it is as completely generalized in temporal-objective-social terms as is conceivable, is not without further ado environmentally effective. A religious sect that has all the possibilities of internal decision-making and decision-making at its disposal may fall victim to ridicule, a political party may find itself in permanent opposition in its political system despite its high internal power. No one will deny the internal power of the Catholic Church in Poland, and yet politically it can be limited to a largely inconsequential presentation of views. Perhaps such borderline cases of functional differentiation are typically unstable because the system, thanks to its decisiveness, can either improve relations with the environment through restructuring or cannot maintain its high internal power in the long term. The applicability of system power in the environment, its effective, useful usability, \"is of course an unthinkable factor in the generalization of internal power."
